## COVID-19 Vaccine Effectiveness and Waning Immunity

### Initial Efficacy

Clinical trials for Pfizer-BioNTech and Moderna vaccines showed efficacy rates of approximately 90-95% against symptomatic COVID-19 infection ([FDA, 2020](https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-takes-key-action-fight-against-covid-19-issuing-emergency-use-authorization-first-covid-19-vaccine)). Johnson & Johnson’s vaccine showed about 66% efficacy ([CNBC, 2021](https://www.cnbc.com/2021/02/04/johnson-johnson-requests-emergency-authorization-from-fda-for-covid-vaccine.html)).

### Real-World Effectiveness

Real-world studies have shown that vaccine effectiveness can decline over time, especially against infection, though protection against severe disease, hospitalization, and death remains strong ([Appleby, 2021](https://khn.org/news/article/what-do-we-really-know-about-vaccine-effectiveness/)).

- A large study of over 3.4 million Kaiser Permanente members showed Pfizer vaccine effectiveness against infection dropped from 88% one month after vaccination to 47% at five to six months, while effectiveness against hospitalization remained around 90% ([Tartof et al., 2021](https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(21)02183-8/fulltext)).

- The emergence of the Delta variant, which is more infectious, also contributed to changes in effectiveness ([Schaffner, 2021](https://www.vumc.org/)).

### Booster Shots

Due to waning immunity, booster doses have been authorized and recommended, particularly for older adults and high-risk groups, to restore and enhance protection ([CDC, 2021](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/vaccines/booster-shot.html)).

---

## Herd Immunity and Population-Level Protection

Even though vaccines are not 100% effective for every individual, widespread vaccination can lead to **herd immunity**, reducing virus circulation and protecting those who are unvaccinated or have weaker immune responses ([Ellis, 2020](https://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-8956485/Why-no-vaccine-100-effective-Wide-variation-populations-immune-systems.html)).

- For measles, achieving over 90% vaccination coverage has led to outbreaks becoming rare.

- For COVID-19, the exact threshold for herd immunity is uncertain due to variants and vaccine effectiveness variability but is estimated to be high due to the virus’s reproduction number ([Irving, 2020](https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/)).

---

## Misconceptions About 100% Effectiveness

- **95% effectiveness does not mean 5% of vaccinated people will get sick.** Instead, it means a vaccinated person has only 5% of the risk of infection compared to an unvaccinated person ([Appleby, 2021](https://khn.org/news/article/what-do-we-really-know-about-vaccine-effectiveness/)).

- Vaccines primarily aim to prevent severe illness and death, not necessarily infection or transmission in all cases.

- Some vaccines, like the whooping cough vaccine, prevent disease but not colonization or transmission, meaning vaccinated individuals can still carry and spread the pathogen ([Ellis, 2020](https://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-8956485/Why-no-vaccine-100-effective-Wide-variation-populations-immune-systems.html)).

---

## Biological Basis for Less Than 100% Effectiveness

### Immune System Variability

- The immune system’s ability to produce effective antibodies depends on genetic factors such as immunoglobulin gene diversity ([Gibson, 2017](https://www.quora.com/Are-vaccines-100-effective-If-not-why-not)).

- Age-related immune senescence reduces vaccine responsiveness in older adults.

- Underlying health conditions (e.g., cancer, immunosuppressive therapy) impair immune responses ([Appleby, 2021](https://khn.org/news/article/what-do-we-really-know-about-vaccine-effectiveness/)).

### Vaccine Composition and Administration

- Some vaccines use weakened or inactivated pathogens, others use mRNA or viral vectors; each has different immune response profiles.

- Booster doses are often needed to maintain or enhance immunity ([Mandal, 2022](https://www.news-medical.net/health/Vaccine-Effectiveness.aspx)).

