---

## Conclusion and Opinion

Based on the comprehensive evidence, **vaccines are not 100% effective** at preventing infection or disease in every individual. This is a biological reality due to immune system variability, pathogen evolution, and practical factors in vaccine administration. However, many vaccines, including COVID-19 vaccines, demonstrate high efficacy and effectiveness, particularly in preventing severe illness, hospitalization, and death.

The goal of vaccination programs is not necessarily to achieve 100% individual protection but to reduce disease burden at the population level through herd immunity and to mitigate severe outcomes. The high efficacy rates of COVID-19 vaccines (90-95% in clinical trials) are remarkable compared to many other vaccines, and real-world effectiveness remains substantial despite waning immunity and variants.

Therefore, while vaccines cannot guarantee absolute protection, their benefits in controlling infectious diseases are profound and indispensable. Continued vaccination, including booster doses, combined with other public health measures, remains critical in managing diseases like COVID-19.

